es actual token consumption against a budget constraint. Unlike the previous behaviors, this can't be validated with mocks—the real API must be called with a typical document to verify that actual token usage stays within the configured limit. Mocking token counts would miss real-world failures where the actual API consumes more tokens than expected.\n\nBehavior 5 addresses rate limiting: when the API returns a rate-limit signal, the module should retry after waiting rather than immediately failing the caller.\n\nThe retry mechanism is deterministic and can be validated with mocks—set up the API to return 429 on the first request and 200 on the second, then verify the module returns the successful response and made exactly two calls. This confirms the retry logic works as intended.\n\nSince the core behavior is straightforward business logic, unit testing with a mocked API is sufficient. Integration testing could validate HTTP protocol details with a mock server, and system testing would involve actual rate limiting, but those add less value here. verify realistic token behavior without hitting the actual API. However, the test description specifically validates against real API responses to ensure accuracy with actual token counting. That distinction matters—mocking token counts wouldn't catch if the real API changed its behavior. So System is genuinely necessary here, making this **true**.\n\nAll five tests have plan_consistent marked as true, which makes sense since each minimum_level was chosen to match what the test actually requires. A mock server could realistically simulate the token counting behavior, making Integration testing viable for catching this failure. However, there's ambiguity about whether the module actively enforces budget limits or simply tracks them. If enforcement happens at the module level through input truncation or similar mechanisms, Unit tests suffice to verify the logic works correctly. If the module only measures usage and relies on