though, the unit test is sufficient. The core concern is whether the module includes the taxonomy in its request, not whether JSON serialization works correctly. I'll use unit testing for this behavior.\n\nLet me finalize my analysis now. Actually, I should double-check the issue description to confirm I'm covering the right behaviors.\n\nThe five behaviors map to: (1) request payload includes taxonomy labels—unit test with mock API; (2) unexpected labels return \"unknown\"—unit test with mock API returning invalid label; (3) repeated calls for the same document yield consistent results—unit test verifying cache behavior; (4) token consumption stays within budget—system test with real API; (5) rate limit handling with retry logic—unit test mocking 429 response.\n\nThese all check out. Though for behavior 3, I should clarify whether the test is verifying that caching works or that the API itself is deterministic. If it's about caching, a unit test suffices. If it's about API determinism, that's a different concern.\n\nFor behavior 4, I'm weighing whether a system test calling the real API is necessary or if an integration test with a mocked API simulating realistic token usage would be sufficient. The real failure mode would be if the actual API consumes more tokens than expected, which only a system test would catch.\n\nAn integration test with a mock could verify the module handles token overages correctly, but without knowing if the mock accurately reflects real API behavior, there's uncertainty. The system test provides definitive validation by confirming actual token consumption against the budget. I'll classify this as system level since validating real API behavior is essential to catching genuine failures. : 0.05 (token count might vary)\n- Workflow: 0.00\n\nToken counts are deterministic API responses, not dependent on LLM non-determinism, so I should lower the Agentic probability to 0.01. Adjusting my final distribution: Unit 0.12, Integration 0.41, System 